{{Quote|Building the set at Yuma was an enormous project... Over Thanksgiving holiday when we first erected the fence around the set, there was a reported crowd of 35,000 dune buggy enthusiasts there. We needed to camouflage ourselves from the public and to schedule our shooting to avoid stray dune buggies creeping into a shot in the distance. This wasn't easy because on weekends the buggies covered the surrounding hills like ants.|Howard Kazanjian|<ref name="ROTJOFC" />}}
[[File:Returnofthejedi1.png|thumb|250px|Chewbacca, Han Solo, and Luke Skywalker on their way to the Great Pit of Carkoon]]
Instead of returning to [[Tunisia]], the filmmakers decided to stay closer to home and go to the sand dunes around '''Yuma''' for making [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']]. Buttercup Valley, [[Wikipedia:California|California]]<ref name="ROTJOFC">''[[Star Wars: Return of the Jedi - Official Collectors Edition]]''</ref> was the filming site for the [[Great Pit of Carkoon]] sequence on the [[Dune Sea]]. Filming took place in April [[1982]], though construction had taken place over the previous five months.<ref name="Yby">''[[Star Wars Year by Year: A Visual Chronicle]]''</ref> The crew stayed in the nearest town, [[Wikipedia:Yuma, Arizona|Yuma]], [[Wikipedia:Arizona|Arizona]], while filming, logging over 5,500 man-days in hotel rooms for set construction and filming.<ref name="ROTJOFC" />

For ''[[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|A New Hope]]''{{'s}} [[The Star Wars Trilogy Special Edition|Special Edition]], the crew returned to the [[Wikipedia:Algodones Dunes|Imperial Sand Dunes]] to film additional shots of [[stormtrooper]]s searching for traces of [[R2-D2]] crash landing his [[escape pod]].<ref>[[Star Wars Insider 48|''Star Wars Insider'' 48]]</ref>

